<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ881020-0043 </DOCNO><HL> Business Brief -- Dow Jones andamp; Co.: Publisher Increases Its Stake In Telerate Common to 57% </HL><SO> </SO><CO> DJ TLR </CO><IN> TNM </IN><TEXT>   Dow Jones andamp; Co. said it acquired one million shares of Telerate Inc. common from Neil S. Hirsch, Telerate president and chief executive officer, for $16.50 a share.    The $16.5 million purchase raises Dow Jones's stake in Telerate to about 57% from about 56%. Telerate currently has 94.8 million average common shares outstanding.    Mr. Hirsch, who founded the New York supplier of computerized financial information, said the sale reduced his personal holdings in Telerate to about 5.7 million shares, or about 6% of the company. &quot;I needed to raise some cash,&quot; he said of the sale. &quot;I'm going through a divorce.&quot;    A spokesman for Dow Jones said in New York that although the company hasn't any immediate plans to buy more Telerate stock, it retains the option to do so, depending on price and availability.    In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday, Telerate closed at $14.625, off 12.5 cents. Dow Jones closed at $34.25, up 25 cents.    Dow Jones publishes The Wall Street Journal, Barron's magazine, other periodicals, electronic business information services and community newspapers. </TEXT></DOC>